DIS: Re: BUS: Indulgence Taxation

I used standard "banking" rounding procedures.  Anything less than .5 is
rounded down; anything greater than .5 is rounded up.  That is, the number is
rounded to the *closest* integer.  Actually, I forget which is the standard way
to round an exact .5 (I think it's up), but since nobody ended up with 80%
equal to exactly n.5 anyway, it's not an issue here.

As to justification - I am interpreting R1853 as requiring me to compute an
amount of tax to be levied on each Player based on eir holdings and some
percentage, but that the indivisibilty of the Currency, as defined by the MUQ
of that Currency, requires this computation be made in units of the MUQ (hence
the need for rounding).  Therefore, IMO, the "amount required by the tax rule"
*is* the rounded figure - not the "raw" rational number generated by the
percentage computation, so that I am not, as you were afraid might be the case,
taxing Players for more than the Rules authorize.  Note that R1853 does not say
I have to bill Players *exactly* N% of their holdings, just that I have to
express the amount of the levy as a percentage when I make the announcement.

-- Crito

