Scott Goehring wrote:
>
>"David" == David Albertz <dalbertz@rmv.state.ma.us> writes:
>
>David> As required by Rule 1853, I hereby issue the following Payment
>David> Orders to satisfy this tax:
>
>Will these Orders result in a distribution (R1712) being required next
>week?  Frankly, I'm getting a bit tired of these constant "Soak the
>Rich" actions.  What's the point of having an economy if we punish
>people who are successful accumulating wealth?

I think that's the wrong metaphor and the wrong question to ask. We are
constantly playtesting the Rules. We introduced Risky Rebellion, and in
the course of playtesting we discovered a bug: a successful Rebellion
takes all the Blots out of the economy without taking Indulgences with
them. (And now Crito has discovered another bug: POs for Indulgences
count as Blots, even if they were issued for the purposes of taxation
and not for penalizing Crimes or Infractions.) Since the concept of
Indulgences as anti-Blots was introduced, there's always been a concern
to make sure that the number of Indulgences in circulation is always
about the same, or slightly less than, the number of Blots, because we
want Indulgences to be highly sought after. To meet that concern, the
discovery of the Rebellion bug necessitated something like an Indulgence
tax. So the right question to ask is: what is the point of persisting
with a wildly unbalanced game state that is the result of a bug?
Especially when the economic aspects of the game that we want to explore
(scarcity, trading), will only be accentuated by correcting the game
state to account for the effects of the bug. It might have taken 6
months for 50 Indulgences to be spent paying off Blots - why should we
wait, given that Indulgence scarcity is what we're really interested in?



